     7	## Solid-2.0 async API set (isPending / refresh / latest)
     8	
     9	1. **Two-level suspense rule is CONTEXT-SENSITIVE** (owner amendment,
    10	   supersedes the context-blind first cut):
    11	   - (a) **Inside a transition pass**: `useSignal` ALWAYS hands the node-held
    12	     thenable to React `use()` — even refresh-pending with a `latest`. React
    13	     natively holds old UI for suspends-in-transition (no fallback flash) and
    14	     keeps the transition pending until settlement, aligning signals-side and
    15	     React-side waiters of the same promise into one commit (no early commit
    16	     with stale data). Pinned by: *"signals-side and React-side waiters of one
    17	     promise commit together"* (both gate modes), *"refresh-in-transition
    18	     converges with stale-hold"* (both gate modes), react-real.test.tsx.
    19	   - (b) **Urgent/sync pass with a settled history** (`box.latest !==
    20	     undefined`): serve `latest` through; pending surfaces via `useIsPending`.
    21	     Suspending here would flash the fallback. Pinned by: *"first-load →
    22	     fallback; refetch → stale stays"* (both gate modes).
    23	   - (c) **Never-settled** (`box.latest === undefined`, our UNINITIALIZED):
    24	     always suspend.
    25	   - Per-site opt-outs are `latest()` / `isPending()` — **no new hook
    26	     variants**.
    27	   - The engine never holds transitions itself; React is the single waiter.
    28	     Settlement writes still commit into the requesting batch's world routing.
    29	
    30	2. **UNINITIALIZED-clears-at-COMMIT equivalent**: Solid clears
    31	   `STATUS_UNINITIALIZED` when the first real value COMMITS at flush, not when
    32	   the promise resolves. Our equivalent: "uninitialized" is
    33	   `box.latest === undefined`, and it disappears exactly when the settlement
    34	   WRITE replaces the box in the drain (`onThenableSettled` → invalidate →
    35	   materializing re-eval) — commit-time, not resolve-time. Any later re-pend
    36	   folds the settled value into the next box's `latest` (`foldEvalResult`), so
    37	   a once-settled node presents as refresh-pending from then on. Settlement
    38	   MATERIALIZES each waiter canonically (Solid's `_blocked`-rerun equivalent) —
    39	   without it an unobserved node's settled value never lands and its next
    40	   re-pend would masquerade as a first load.
    41	
    42	3. **`refresh` and the ctx.use re-registration mechanism**: this engine re-runs
    43	   the fn at settlement, so resource fns must return a STABLE thenable per
    44	   logical request (fresh-promise-per-run fns would livelock). "Clear thenable
    45	   slots" therefore has no positional referent; the ergonomic equivalent is a
    46	   per-node **refresh epoch** exposed as `ctx.refreshEpoch` — resource fns key
    47	   their request cache on `(params, refreshEpoch)` and a refresh mints a fresh
    48	   thenable. `refresh()` = epoch bump + invalidation shaped like the settlement
    49	   write (worlds re-derive; live writer worlds re-decide) + an eager canonical
    50	   eval that starts the refetch and folds the pre-refresh value into
    51	   `box.latest` (refresh-pending, never uninitialized). No-op on atoms.
    52	   Latest-wins: a superseded settlement re-runs the fn, which re-registers the
    53	   CURRENT request.
    54	
    55	4. **`latest` world choice is the ambient world** (no staged buffer — world
    56	   reads are the answer): top level = NEWEST (in-flight values visible, the
    57	   Solid staged-read asymmetry); inside a computed/overlay eval = that eval's
    58	   world (world consistency is load-bearing for memo certificates); inside a
    59	   render pass = the pass's world (render purity/replay); inside
    60	   `withRootCommitted` = the root's committed view. Deviation from Solid: a
    61	   committed-pass component cannot sample the in-flight world via `latest`
    62	   (that would tear a pure replay); it uses `useIsPending` instead.
    63	
    64	5. **`isPending` deviations from Solid §2.3**: our probe never suspends —
    65	   first-load pending inside a reactive context returns `false` rather than
    66	   rethrowing to suspend the boundary (Solid rethrows for
    67	   uninitialized-first-load). Flip-only is exact: the probe is a cached
    68	   `Computed<boolean>` over box shape; boolean equality suppresses upstream
    69	   value churn.
    70	
    71	## §ambient-W0 — ambient read semantics (owner-approved, alt-a/alt-b ONLY)
    72	
    73	**Recorded divergence**: mainline cosignal keeps NEWEST-ambient; the alt
    74	family switches ambient reads to W0. Deliberate, per owner decision — never
    75	leak one family's expectation into the other (shared/ported tests must be
    76	parameterized per family: alt = drafts-hidden, cosignal = NEWEST).
    77	
    78	1. **Ambient top-level/handler `.state` = W0** (committed + applied urgent).
    79	   Pending DEFERRED batches are INVISIBLE outside their own context until
    80	   commit. Rationale: an urgent handler deriving from `.state` must never
    81	   leak a speculative draft into committed state (the onClick scenario:
    82	   transition `set(1)`; urgent `set(state*2)` computes `0*2` and supersedes
    83	   the transition — pinned in RTL, both gate modes; abort leaves no
    84	   contamination — pinned in overlay + oracle `readOwnDraft`/ambient ops).
    85	2. **Read-your-own-draft**: inside a deferred batch's own write scope
    86	   (`ForkDouble.inBatch`, a React transition scope) or its render pass,
    87	   ambient reads resolve that batch's world. Urgent scopes and `batch()`
    88	   read-own-writes unchanged (their writes are APPLIED — W0 includes them;
    89	   conformance-critical). The gate decides LOGGED vs DIRECT, not visibility —
    90	   asserted in both gate modes. ReactFork probe: `(T === lastMintT)` identity
    91	   on the reconciler's current-transition slot, token recorded at the scope's
    92	   first minting write; reads before any write correctly see W0.
    93	3. **`latest(x)` is THE explicit Wn read (drafts included)** — supersedes the
    94	   earlier deviation where in-render world choice was the only distinction.
    95	   Per-context table (reconciled with alt-a on the top-level outcome):
    96	   - plain top level / handlers / engine effects: **Wn including unapplied
    97	     drafts** (matches alt-a's spec'd outcome);
    98	   - inside a computed/overlay eval: that eval's world (memo-certificate
    99	     integrity — sampling Wn would poison per-world memos);
   100	   - inside a render pass: the pass's world Wp (replay purity; a committed
   101	     pass never tears an in-flight sample — reasoning documented, our call);
   102	   - inside withRootCommitted: the root's committed view.
   103	4. **`committed(x)` / `useCommitted`**: explicit committed-world read over the
   104	   existing withRootCommitted/committed-view machinery (root-refined when a
   105	   root scope is active; global otherwise — the hook is global, since hooks
   106	   do not know their root). Box handling mirrors `.state` + two-level rule.
   107	5. **Perf**: ambient reads under live deferred batches now take the kernel
   108	   fast path (W0 IS the kernel state) instead of overlay resolution — G-8
   109	   ambient-read ratio drops to ~1.0x (see report); the Wn cost is paid only
   110	   by explicit `latest()` and render-pass reads.
   111	
   112	## §lazy-init — lazy state initializers (owner-approved feature, both alts)
   113	
   114	`new Atom({ state: () => T })` / `new ReducerAtom({ state: () => S, ... })` /
   115	`useAtom({ state: () => T })`:
   116	
   117	1. **React useState convention**: function-valued `state` IS the initializer —
   118	   evaluated ONCE, lazily, at first materialization (never at construction).
   119	   Storing a function as state requires the wrap: `state: () => fn`
   120	   (documented on `AtomOptions.state` with the `documentVisible` recipe — an
   121	   SSR-safe environment probe whose module-scope construction never touches
   122	   `document`).
   123	2. **Untracked + graph-pure**: the initializer runs with tracking suppressed
   124	   (its reads link nothing — pinned: a computed that materializes the atom
   125	   does not inherit the initializer's deps) and writes inside it are rejected
   126	   in debug. A throwing initializer re-runs on the next read (React retry
   127	   semantics); a cyclic initializer (reads its own atom) throws a clear error.
   128	3. **Render-context safe**: first read during a render pass materializes —
   129	   it is a pure slot fill (both value slots), not a write: no propagation, no
   130	   watchers, no §10.8 violation. Nothing can have observed the atom before
   131	   materialization, so filling the slot is invisible by construction.
   132	4. **Write-before-first-read (decision: RUN the initializer)** — the write
   133	   path's equality compare (`pendingAtomValue`) materializes first, so
   134	   `set(initValue)` on an untouched lazy atom is correctly dropped by the
   135	   equality contract, and `update(fn)`/`dispatch(a)` receive the initializer
   136	   result. Both gate modes pinned (the gate decides LOGGED vs DIRECT; both
   137	   compare through the same accessor).
   138	5. **Tape/base-snapshot**: `createTape`'s base snapshot reads through
   139	   `pendingAtomValue`, so a DRAFT-world first touch bases the tape on the
   140	   initializer result — canonical base state, never draft-scoped (pinned:
   141	   W0/committed read the init value while the writer world shows the draft).
   142	6. **SSR**: `installState` IS the materialization — the initializer is
   143	   skipped (slot fill + `lazyInit` cleared; sound because an unmaterialized
   144	   atom has no observers).
   145	7. **Mechanism**: a unique symbol sentinel occupies both value slots; the two
   146	   base accessors (`kernelAtomValue`, `pendingAtomValue`) test one identity
   147	   compare on the hot path — every other path (worlds, folds, peeks, watcher
   148	   seeding) routes through them. The initializer lives in the meta column.
   149	
   150	## Open API questions
   151	
   152	- **`suspend: 'always'` option**: should a computed (or hook call site) be able
   153	  to opt INTO suspension for urgent refetches — i.e. force rule (a) behavior in
   154	  urgent passes, flashing the fallback intentionally (e.g. paginated views that
   155	  must not show stale rows)? Deferred; today the urgent path always serves
   156	  stale, and there is no per-site way to demand a fallback. Recorded
   157	  per owner instruction — do not implement without a decision.

