     6	
     7	## Solid-2.0 async API set (isPending / refresh / latest)
     8	
     9	1. **Two-level suspense rule is CONTEXT-SENSITIVE** (owner amendment,
    10	   supersedes the context-blind first cut):
    11	   - (a) **Inside a transition pass**: `useSignal` ALWAYS hands the node-held
    12	     thenable to React `use()` — even refresh-pending with a `latest`. React
    13	     natively holds old UI for suspends-in-transition (no fallback flash) and
    14	     keeps the transition pending until settlement, aligning signals-side and
    15	     React-side waiters of the same promise into one commit (no early commit
    16	     with stale data). Pinned by: *"signals-side and React-side waiters of one
    17	     promise commit together"* (both gate modes), *"refresh-in-transition
    18	     converges with stale-hold"* (both gate modes), react-real.test.tsx.
    19	   - (b) **Urgent/sync pass with a settled history** (`box.latest !==
    20	     undefined`): serve `latest` through; pending surfaces via `useIsPending`.
    21	     Suspending here would flash the fallback. Pinned by: *"first-load →
    22	     fallback; refetch → stale stays"* (both gate modes).
    23	   - (c) **Never-settled** (`box.latest === undefined`, our UNINITIALIZED):
    24	     always suspend.
    25	   - Per-site opt-outs are `latest()` / `isPending()` — **no new hook
    26	     variants**.
    27	   - The engine never holds transitions itself; React is the single waiter.
    28	     Settlement writes still commit into the requesting batch's world routing.
    29	
    30	2. **UNINITIALIZED-clears-at-COMMIT equivalent**: Solid clears
    31	   `STATUS_UNINITIALIZED` when the first real value COMMITS at flush, not when
    32	   the promise resolves. Our equivalent: "uninitialized" is
    33	   `box.latest === undefined`, and it disappears exactly when the settlement
    34	   WRITE replaces the box in the drain (`onThenableSettled` → invalidate →
    35	   materializing re-eval) — commit-time, not resolve-time. Any later re-pend
    36	   folds the settled value into the next box's `latest` (`foldEvalResult`), so
    37	   a once-settled node presents as refresh-pending from then on. Settlement
    38	   MATERIALIZES each waiter canonically (Solid's `_blocked`-rerun equivalent) —
    39	   without it an unobserved node's settled value never lands and its next
    40	   re-pend would masquerade as a first load.
    41	
    42	3. **`refresh` and the ctx.use re-registration mechanism**: this engine re-runs
    43	   the fn at settlement, so resource fns must return a STABLE thenable per
    44	   logical request (fresh-promise-per-run fns would livelock). "Clear thenable
    45	   slots" therefore has no positional referent; the ergonomic equivalent is a
    46	   per-node **refresh epoch** exposed as `ctx.refreshEpoch` — resource fns key
    47	   their request cache on `(params, refreshEpoch)` and a refresh mints a fresh
    48	   thenable. `refresh()` = epoch bump + invalidation shaped like the settlement
    49	   write (worlds re-derive; live writer worlds re-decide) + an eager canonical
    50	   eval that starts the refetch and folds the pre-refresh value into
    51	   `box.latest` (refresh-pending, never uninitialized). No-op on atoms.
    52	   Latest-wins: a superseded settlement re-runs the fn, which re-registers the
    53	   CURRENT request.
    54	
    55	4. **`latest` world choice is the ambient world** (no staged buffer — world
    56	   reads are the answer): top level = NEWEST (in-flight values visible, the
    57	   Solid staged-read asymmetry); inside a computed/overlay eval = that eval's
