   585	## 6. The React fork
   586	
   587	We maintain a fork of React (a submodule + build script; see 6.7) whose only
   588	substantive addition is a small, renderer-agnostic introspection channel
   589	called the **external runtime**. The channel's protocol is
   590	**integer-oriented**: batch identities cross the boundary as plain integers
   591	rather than objects, which lets the engine stamp them straight into
   592	`Int32Array` log records with no interning `Map` on the write path.
   593	
   594	Design constraints, in order:
   595	
   596	1. **React-concurrency-safe.** The protocol must describe batches and passes
   597	   truthfully across lane recycling, yielding, restarts, multi-root commits,
   598	   and async actions. Everything here is *edge-triggered from the places the
   599	   reconciler already mutates its own bookkeeping* — never sampled — so it
   600	   cannot drift from reality.
   601	2. **Minimal and encapsulating.** No Fiber objects, no lane bitmasks, no
   602	   reconciler types cross the boundary. Tokens are serially-numbered
   603	   integers, uncorrelated with lane bit positions. Roots are identified by
   604	   their *container* (for react-dom, the DOM element you rendered into) — an
   605	   identity that is meaningful to userspace anyway.
   606	3. **Inert when unused.** Every hook site is one null/flag check when nothing
   607	   has subscribed. The additions carry no feature flag; they simply do
   608	   nothing without a listener.
   609	
   610	### 6.1 The isomorphic API (exports from `react`)
   611	
   612	```ts
   613	type Container = unknown  // e.g. the DOM element passed to createRoot
   614	
   615	type ExternalRuntimeListener = {
   616	  /** A render pass began on `container`. `includedBatches` are the tokens of
   617	   * every live batch this pass renders. `lineage` is a stable integer naming
   618	   * this piece of render work across its restarts and Suspense retries (6.3).
   619	   * A pass spans yields; it ends by completing or being discarded/restarted. */
   620	  onRenderPassStart?: (container: Container, includedBatches: readonly number[], lineage: number) => void
   621	  /** The pass on `container` completed or was discarded. Exactly one end per
   622	   * start, even across restarts. */
   623	  onRenderPassEnd?: (container: Container) => void
   624	  /** The pass on `container` is yielding to the event loop (time-slicing)
   625	   * without ending; onRenderPassResume fires when it picks work back up.
   626	   * Yield and resume alternate strictly between one start and its end.
   627	   * Event handlers, timers, and microtasks run inside yield gaps — reads and
   628	   * writes there are NOT render-phase reads and writes (10.1). */
   629	  onRenderPassYield?: (container: Container) => void
   630	  onRenderPassResume?: (container: Container) => void
   631	  /** A batch's work committed on one root — exactly once per (token, root),
   632	   * at the moment that root's commit finishes. Fires before onBatchRetired
   633	   * when this is the token's last pending root. Feeds the per-root committed
   634	   * views (13.4). */
   635	  onBatchCommitted?: (container: Container, token: number) => void
   636	  /** A batch retired — exactly once per token, ever. `committed` is false
   637	   * only for batches that never produced React work (external-only writes);
   638	   * batches whose React updates died with unmounted trees still retire
   639	   * through an ordinary (possibly empty) commit with committed = true. */
   640	  onBatchRetired?: (token: number, committed: boolean) => void
   641	  /** DOM mutation window; see 6.6. */
   642	  onBeforeMutation?: (container: Container) => void
   643	  onAfterMutation?: (container: Container) => void
   644	}
   645	
   646	function unstable_subscribeToExternalRuntime(l: ExternalRuntimeListener): () => void
   647	
   648	/** Would a write issued right now belong to a deferred (transition-like)
   649	 * batch? Pure classification: no minting, no allocation. */
   650	function unstable_isCurrentWriteDeferred(): boolean
   651	
   652	/** The token of the batch a write issued right now belongs to, minting it on
   653	 * first use. 0 when no renderer is loaded. */
   654	function unstable_getCurrentWriteBatch(): number
   655	
   656	/** undefined outside render; the rendering root's container during render.
   657	 * (The signals engine uses "am I inside render?" and "which root?" — nothing
   658	 * else leaks.) */
   659	function unstable_getRenderContext(): { container: Container } | undefined
   660	
   661	/** Batch entanglement: run `fn` so that any React updates it schedules are
   662	 * assigned to the SAME batch as `token` — they render and retire with it.
   663	 * Returns false (without running `fn`) if the token has already retired;
   664	 * the caller must then fall back to a plain urgent update. Section 6.5. */
   665	function unstable_runInBatch(token: number, fn: () => void): boolean
   666	```
   667	
   668	Renderers (react-dom, test renderers) register a provider on the shared
   669	internals object at module init, following React's existing
   670	`ReactSharedInternals` slot pattern; the isomorphic functions above delegate
   671	to it. With multiple renderers loaded simultaneously, write attribution
   672	answers from the first registered provider (documented limitation — only one
   673	renderer processes an event at a time in practice).
   674	
   675	### 6.2 Batch tokens: integer protocol
   676	
   677	A **batch token** names "a set of updates React renders and retires as a
   678	unit". Why not expose React's lane bits directly? Lane bits are *recycled*
   679	(the transition lane cursor wraps after a handful of claims), so a bit cannot
   680	name a batch across time; and lane bits are exactly the reconciler internal
   681	we refuse to leak. Tokens are identities.
   682	
   683	Encoding:
   684	
   685	- `token = (serial << 1) | (deferred ? 1 : 0)`, where `serial` starts at 1
   686	  and increments per minted token. Tokens are nonzero 31-bit integers — they
   687	  are Smis in V8, they fit in an `Int32Array` slot, and bit 0 answers "is
   688	  this transition-like?" without a lookup.
   689	- `0` means "no token" everywhere.
   690	- Serials are never reused while any token is live. At the 2^30 wrap
   691	  (unreachable in practice: one serial per *event or transition that touches
   692	  external state*), the registry skips serials still held by its ≤31 live
   693	  slots.
   694	
   695	**Liveness invariant: at most 31 tokens are live at once** — one per lane
   696	slot. If React reuses a lane bit while the registry still holds a pending
   697	token for it, React itself cannot tell the two batches apart (they render and
   698	retire together), so the registry reuses the existing token: an explicit
   699	merge that mirrors reality. This invariant is what lets the engine intern
   700	tokens into a fixed table of 32 batch slots (section 9.2).
   701	
   702	Registry edges (each wired into a place the reconciler already touches):
   703	
   704	- **claim** — a transition claims a lane for the current event
   705	  (`requestTransitionLane`); slot noted, no allocation.
   706	- **mint** — first `unstable_getCurrentWriteBatch()` call for the slot
   707	  creates the token. Writes that never ask cost nothing.
   708	- **pending** — `markRootUpdated`: the batch has scheduled work on a root;
   709	  the slot records the root. A repair pass (**backfill**) runs in the root
   710	  scheduler's microtask to catch updates scheduled *before* the batch's first
   711	  store write (ordinary `startTransition(() => { setState(x); atom.set(y) })`
   712	  line order).
   713	- **finish** — after `markRootFinished` in commit: a batch is done on a root
   714	  when its lane is no longer pending there. The token retires when its *last*
   715	  pending root finishes. If a root commits the batch while other roots are
   716	  still pending, that root is recorded in the slot's committed set: later
   717	  renders on it must keep including the batch (its committed tree already
   718	  shows those values — hiding them would tear the root against its own DOM).
   719	  `batchTokensForRender` folds these locked-in tokens into
   720	  `includedBatches`.
   721	- **close** — end of the event's scheduling microtask: a batch that produced
   722	  no React work anywhere retires now with `committed = false` — with one
   723	  exception: a store-only transition whose scope returned a promise (an
   724	  **async action**) parks on that promise and re-runs the close decision when
   725	  it settles, because the action's post-await updates commit later and
   726	  retiring early would leak its writes into canonical state mid-action.
   727	
   728	These edges and their exact reconciler call sites were built and
   729	reconciler-test-suite-validated in the previous-generation fork; this design
   730	inherits them wholesale and changes only the token representation
   731	(object → integer) plus the entanglement entry point (6.5). The per-edge cost
   732	with no live tokens is an integer/null check.
   733	
   734	### 6.3 Render passes, yields, and lineage
   735	
   736	`onRenderPassStart(container, includedBatches, lineage)` fires when React
   737	prepares a fresh work-in-progress stack for a root with real work;
   738	`onRenderPassEnd(container)` fires when that pass completes or is discarded.
   739	Yields do **not** end a pass: a pass paused for time-slicing and resumed
   740	later is one pass, which is exactly why the engine pins the seq counter at
   741	pass start (reads must not move for the pass's whole life). A restart
   742	(fresh stack) ends the old pass and starts a new one, re-delivering
   743	`includedBatches` — the new pass may legitimately see newer state.
   744	
   745	**Yield edges are protocol, not detail.** A time-sliced pass returns to the
   746	event loop *while remaining open*; user code — click handlers, timers,
   747	resolved promises — runs in those gaps. That is the whole point of
   748	concurrent rendering, and it means "a pass is open" and "we are executing
   749	render code right now" are different facts. The engine keeps a read-context
   750	scalar that must track the second fact (10.1), and it deliberately never
   751	consults the fork per read; so the fork delivers the transitions as edges:
   752	`onRenderPassYield` when the work loop's should-yield check makes it leave,
   753	`onRenderPassResume` when it re-enters. Both are wired where the work loop
   754	already knows it is leaving/re-entering; both are one null check when
   755	nothing subscribed. Without these two edges, a write from a click handler
   756	inside a yield gap would look like a render-phase write (which must throw,
   757	10.8) — the design's flagship scenario, an urgent update during a background
   758	render, would crash on first exercise.
   759	
   760	**Lineage names the work, not the pass.** React can restart a pass, and
   761	Suspense re-renders arrive as *new* passes when a promise settles. Anything
   762	cached "for this render" under a per-pass key would be discarded and
   763	re-created on every retry — for suspense caches that means re-fetching
   764	forever, never converging. And a single batch token under-identifies the
   765	work: a pass legitimately renders several entangled batches at once. So the
   766	fork assigns a **render lineage**: a serially-numbered integer minted when a
   767	root first schedules work for a given lane set, redelivered on every pass
   768	start for that same work — across yields, restarts, and Suspense retries —
   769	and retired when that work commits or is abandoned. Per-world suspense
   770	caches key on it (12.3).
   771	
   772	`includedBatches` contains the live tokens for the pass's render lanes plus
   773	the committed-elsewhere lock-ins from 6.2. Tokens whose batches carry no
   774	external writes are simply unknown to the engine and ignored.
   775	
   776	React renders one pass at a time on a thread; passes on different roots never
   777	interleave *execution* (switching roots restarts). The engine may therefore
   778	keep a single "current pass" scalar set.
   779	
   780	### 6.4 Write classification
   781	
   782	`unstable_isCurrentWriteDeferred()` answers "if setState were called right
   783	now, would it be a transition-like update?" — it is the same decision
   784	`requestUpdateLane` makes, exposed as a boolean. The engine calls it on every
   785	logged write *before* deciding whether to also apply the write directly
   786	(section 9.4); it must therefore be pure and allocation-free, and it is: a
   787	couple of comparisons against the reconciler's current-transition state.
   788	
   789	### 6.5 Batch entanglement (`unstable_runInBatch`)
   790	
   791	The problem this solves: a component can subscribe to a signal *after* a
   792	pending deferred batch already wrote to it (the component mounted, or first
   793	read the signal, in the gap between that batch's write and this component's
   794	commit). The component must now be re-rendered *as part of that batch* — its
   795	corrective update has to render with the batch's other updates and commit in
   796	the same frame. Wrapping the corrective `setState` in a fresh
   797	`startTransition` is **not** enough: `startTransition` starts a *new*
   798	transition, which may be assigned a different lane, render separately, and
   799	commit at a different time. A frame could commit where the batch's other
   800	components show the new world and this component shows the old one — a tear
   801	we introduced ourselves. Only the reconciler knows which lanes a batch
   802	occupies, so only the fork can offer this operation.
   803	
   804	Semantics of `unstable_runInBatch(token, fn)`:
   805	
   806	- **Token live** (registry slot still holds it): the registry looks up the
   807	  lane(s) the batch currently occupies on each of its pending roots. It runs
   808	  `fn` with the reconciler's update-lane selection overridden so that every
   809	  update scheduled inside `fn` is assigned to exactly those lanes — the same
   810	  override scope React itself uses when replaying updates. For a deferred
   811	  batch this also sets the current-transition context, so
   812	  `isCurrentWriteDeferred()` answers true inside `fn` and any signal writes
   813	  inside `fn` log under the same batch token (the engine's slot lookup in
   814	  9.2 sees the same token). Returns true.
   815	- **Token retired**: returns false without running `fn`. The caller falls
   816	  back to a plain urgent update — correct, because a retired batch's values
   817	  have already been absorbed into canonical state, so an urgent re-render
   818	  reads them anyway.
   819	- **Reentrancy**: `runInBatch` may be called from inside a commit-phase
   820	  effect (that is its primary call site, section 13.2). It must not flush
   821	  synchronously; it only tags the scheduled updates. Nesting `runInBatch`
   822	  inside `runInBatch` or inside `startTransition` is defined to use the
   823	  innermost override.
   824	
   825	Because the update lands in the batch's own lanes, React's existing machinery
   826	does the rest: the batch's next render pass includes the corrective update,
   827	`includedBatches` is unchanged (same token), and the batch retires once, with
   828	the correction inside it. The reconciler test suite gains a test asserting
   829	exactly this: schedule work in a transition, subscribe late, entangle a
   830	corrective update, and observe **one** commit containing both (section 17.6).
   831	
   832	One registry detail makes this sound: the **finish** edge (6.2) retires a
   833	token only when its last pending root finishes. An entangled update scheduled
   834	during the commit phase of that final root arrives before `markRootFinished`
   835	completes the retirement decision for the lane — the registry treats the
   836	newly scheduled work as re-pending the token (the same rule that handles
   837	multi-root spans). So the "token live" check inside `runInBatch` is not a
   838	race window: either the token is still pending somewhere and the update joins
   839	it, or retirement already happened and the caller takes the urgent fallback.
   840	
   841	### 6.6 The DOM mutation window
   842	
   843	Unrelated to signals, delivered on the same channel because it is the same
   844	kind of lifecycle fact: `onBeforeMutation(container)` /
   845	`onAfterMutation(container)` bracket exactly the window in which React
   846	mutates the host tree during a commit, so an application `MutationObserver`
   847	can disconnect around React's own writes and observe everything else. The
   848	signals library itself never references MutationObserver.
