  2310	
  2311	## 13. React bindings
  2312	
  2313	All bindings share one module-level singleton: the **bridge**. At first
  2314	import it subscribes to the external runtime (6.1) and wires the callbacks:
  2315	
  2316	- `onRenderPassStart(container, tokens, lineage)` → `passOpen = 1;
  2317	  passSerial++; passPin = seqCounter; passIncludeMask = internAll(tokens);
  2318	  passContainer = container; passLineage = lineage` — and switch the read
  2319	  context to `RENDER`. Batch-open edges also flip `writeMode` to `LOGGED`
  2320	  if it was not already (9.1).
  2321	- `onRenderPassYield(container)` / `onRenderPassResume(container)` → flip
  2322	  the read context `RENDER ↔ NEWEST`; the pass set persists (10.1).
  2323	- `onRenderPassEnd(container)` → close the pass, restore `NEWEST`, run a
  2324	  sweep (9.6).
  2325	- `onBatchCommitted(container, token)` → update the container's committed
  2326	  view (13.4) and flush that root's `useSignalEffect` watchers in a
  2327	  microtask, filtered by that view.
  2328	- `onBatchRetired(token, committed)` → retirement + absorption (9.5); the
  2329	  quiescence check may then revert `writeMode` to `DIRECT` (9.7).
  2330	- `onBeforeMutation`/`onAfterMutation` → re-emitted verbatim on
  2331	  `cosignal/react`'s own tiny event surface for app code (MutationObserver
  2332	  users); the signals engine ignores them.
  2333	
  2334	### 13.1 The watcher protocol
  2335	
  2336	A mounted `useSignal`/`useComputed` owns one **watcher node** (kind
  2337	`K_WATCHER`, flags `WATCHING|IMMEDIATE|LIVE`). Its `fns` entry is the
  2338	broadcast closure; its meta holds `lastBroadcast` per-world memos (10.6).
  2339	Watchers subscribe like effects — a link from the watched node — but notify
  2340	through the broadcast list, synchronously in the writer's stack:
  2341	
  2342	```
  2343	broadcast():  // called by the write wrapper's drain loop
  2344	  if worldValueChanged(watchedId, writerWorld):   // 10.6 cutoff
  2345	      setVersion(v => (v + 1) | 0)                // the hook's useState
  2346	```
  2347	
  2348	Because `setVersion` runs in the writer's context, React's
  2349	`requestUpdateLane` gives the re-render the writer's priority: transition
  2350	writes schedule transition re-renders, urgent writes schedule urgent
  2351	re-renders, updates inside async actions entangle — all inherited, never
  2352	reimplemented. Every signal-driven render passes through React's
  2353	infinite-loop guards (`NESTED_UPDATE_LIMIT`, render-phase re-render limit)
  2354	like any setState.
  2355	
  2356	### 13.2 `useSignal(signal)`
  2357	
  2358	Render phase (pure): read the signal in `RENDER` context (which resolves the
  2359	pass's world Wp) and return it. A mount *during* a transition render
  2360	therefore reads the pending world directly — no double render, no guessing;
  2361	this is the scenario stock-React userland provably cannot handle (the
  2362	known-bug test we inherit and turn green, 17.6). If the value is a
  2363	`SuspendedBox`, call React's `use(thenable)` — a conditional `use` is legal —
  2364	so Suspense fallbacks and replays behave exactly as for a suspending
  2365	`useState` initializer.
  2366	
  2367	Commit phase (layout effect): create/rebind the watcher node and link it to
  2368	the signal, then run the **post-subscribe fixup** for writes that raced into
  2369	the gap between render and subscription. The watcher remembers the world
  2370	(pin + include mask) and value it rendered with; both checks are
  2371	**world-aware** — they re-resolve the node and compare values, never
  2372	compare world identities, because "the committed value moved past what we
  2373	rendered" is *expected*, not a race, whenever the rendered world included a
  2374	still-pending batch (this component just rendered inside transition k's
  2375	pass; committed state excludes k by definition — a literal
  2376	committed-vs-rendered comparison would fire a spurious correction on every
  2377	such mount):
  2378	
  2379	- **Did this component's own world move?** Re-resolve the watched node in
  2380	  the watcher's remembered rendered world, *now*, and compare with the
  2381	  remembered value (by the node's equality). A difference means something
  2382	  raced into the gap that the rendered world would have shown — an urgent
  2383	  write, an absorption. Correct it with `setVersion` immediately, in the
  2384	  layout effect's own (urgent) context — a pre-paint correction, the same
  2385	  shape React uses for its own layout-effect updates. If the rendered
  2386	  world's batches have all retired (the world is no longer resolvable), the
  2387	  committed-value comparison is the correct degenerate form and is used as
  2388	  the fallback.
  2389	- **Did a pending world this component missed move?** For each live
  2390	  deferred batch slot whose tape entries affect the watched node, evaluate
  2391	  the node in that batch's writer's world (10.2, memoized per 10.5) and
  2392	  compare with the rendered value. For each batch where the value differs,
  2393	  issue the corrective `setVersion` through the fork's batch-entanglement
  2394	  API: `unstable_runInBatch(token, () => setVersion(bump))`. The correction
  2395	  is thereby assigned to the pending batch's own lanes — it renders with
  2396	  that batch and commits in that batch's frame (6.5). If `runInBatch`
  2397	  returns false, the batch retired between our check and the call; its
  2398	  values are already absorbed into committed state, so the first check
  2399	  covers it — the fixup re-runs the first comparison and falls back to that
  2400	  path.
  2401	
  2402	Why `startTransition` around the corrective setState would be wrong, and why
  2403	entanglement is required: a fresh `startTransition` mints a *new* batch with
  2404	its own lanes and its own commit. React would be free to commit the original
  2405	batch first — without this component's correction — and paint a frame where
  2406	sibling components show the transition's world and this component shows the
  2407	world it rendered a beat too early. The entangled update cannot exhibit that
  2408	frame: it is in the original batch's lanes, so that batch's render includes
  2409	it and that batch's single commit carries it. The test in 17.6 holds a
  2410	transition open, mounts a late subscriber, and asserts exactly one commit,
  2411	containing both the transition's updates and the correction.
  2412	
  2413	Both fixup checks compare against the watcher's remembered render world;
  2414	they fire only in genuine race windows. Unmount: unlink the watcher;
  2415	liveness sweeps run post-commit.
  2416	
  2417	### 13.3 `useComputed(fn, deps, options?)`
  2418	
  2419	A component-local `Computed` held in a `useState` holder, recreated when
  2420	`deps` change (compared like `useMemo`). `fn` closes over props/state freely
  2421	— that is exactly what `deps` re-creation handles; signal reads inside `fn`
  2422	are auto-tracked by the graph (in canonical contexts) and resolved per-world
  2423	during passes. Subscription and reads then work exactly like `useSignal` on
  2424	the local node. Disposal on unmount (and holder replacement) frees the
  2425	record deterministically.
  2426	
  2427	### 13.4 `useSignalEffect(fn, deps?)` and per-root committed views
  2428	
  2429	A passive-effect-scheduled graph watcher over **committed** state: the
  2430	callback runs after commit, reads in `COMMITTED` context, and re-runs when
  2431	(a) `deps` change (React pathway) or (b) the committed value of anything it
  2432	tracked changes (engine pathway, flushed in a microtask after the owning
  2433	root's commit — "after commit", matching `useEffect`'s contract). Cleanup
  2434	supported.
  2435	
  2436	"Committed" here is **per root**. Commits are per-root events: a batch
  2437	spanning two roots commits on root A while still pending on root B, and at
  2438	that moment root A's effects must see the batch's values (root A's DOM
  2439	already shows them — reading older state would put the effect behind its own
  2440	root's screen) while root B's effects must not (nothing committed there
  2441	yet). The global retired-only view can express neither side of that moment.
  2442	So the bridge keeps a small per-container table, updated on
  2443	`onBatchCommitted(container, token)` (6.1):
  2444	
  2445	- `committedPin[container]` — a fresh seq ticket taken at that root's
  2446	  commit; entries retired at or below it are in the root's committed view;
  2447	- `committedMask[container]` — the batch slots this root has committed while
  2448	  their tokens remain pending elsewhere (the bindings-side mirror of the
  2449	  fork's lock-in set, 6.2); entries of those batches are in the view too.
  2450	  When such a token finally retires everywhere, its slot bit clears and the
  2451	  pin advances past its retirement ticket — the view's contents are
  2452	  unchanged by that bookkeeping step.
  2453	
  2454	A `useSignalEffect` callback resolves reads against its own root's view, and
  2455	the engine-pathway flush runs per root commit, filtered by that root's view
  2456	— an effect re-runs when *its root's* committed world changed, not when any
  2457	token anywhere retired. SSR and rootless committed reads (a devtools dump,
  2458	say) use the global retired-only form (10.2). The table is a handful of
  2459	integers per live root, owned by the bindings; node records know nothing of
  2460	roots.
  2461	
  2462	### 13.5 `useAtom` / `useReducerAtom`
  2463	
  2464	Component-owned atoms: created in a `useState` initializer, disposed in the
  2465	unmount cleanup of an effect, recreated on strict-mode remount (the holder
  2466	pattern from the react-concurrent-store harness). They are ordinary atoms —
  2467	other components' computeds may read them through context or props.
  2468	
  2469	### 13.6 Transitions helpers
  2470	
  2471	`startSignalTransition(scope)` = `startTransition` + engine `batch()`: the
  2472	batch coalesces broadcasts so N writes notify each watcher once (one notify
  2473	walk ticket, one drain — 9.8). `useSignalTransition()` wraps `useTransition`
  2474	the same way; `isPending` is React's own. Neither is required for
  2475	correctness — plain `startTransition` works — they are throughput helpers.
  2476	
  2477	### 13.7 Multiple roots
  2478	
  2479	The engine keeps no per-root state beyond the current pass (one pass executes
  2480	at a time, 6.3). Batches spanning roots are correct by construction:
  2481	per-root commit lock-in lives in the fork's registry (6.2), which keeps
  2482	including a committed-elsewhere batch in that root's `includedBatches` until
  2483	the token retires everywhere; the engine just applies the mask it is given.
  2484	
  2485	### 13.8 SSR and hydration
  2486	
  2487	Server rendering uses `COMMITTED` context reads with no subscriptions and no
  2488	observed-lifecycle mounting (watcher creation is a layout-effect concern, and
  2489	layout effects don't run on the server). On the server the write gate never
  2490	leaves DIRECT (no fork activity), so SSR pays zero overlay cost. No
  2491	`getServerSnapshot` analogue exists because reads are plain values. Flight/
  2492	RSC is out of scope for v1.
  2493	
  2494	**Per-request engine isolation.** A Node server interleaves requests, and
  2495	with streaming SSR two renders are genuinely concurrent on one process — a
  2496	module-singleton engine would leak one request's atom values into another's
  2497	HTML. Server builds therefore construct **one engine instance per request**:
  2498	`cosignal/server` exports `createServerEngine()`, returning an isolated
  2499	engine (its own planes, side columns, and handle factories — the same API
  2500	surface, no shared globals). Request handlers create atoms through their
  2501	request's engine; the per-request cost is the initial plane allocation,
  2502	which the `configure` sizing options keep small for server use. The browser
  2503	keeps the module singleton — one interactive document, one engine.
  2504	
