  1280	
  1281	### 9.1 When logging happens at all: the quiescence gate
  1282	
  1283	`writeMode` is `LOGGED` whenever React is **nonquiescent** — any live batch
  1284	token, any pending (unretired) batch, or any render pass in flight — and
  1285	`DIRECT` only at full React quiescence. Both flips ride fork-signaled
  1286	boundaries, so the gate can never race a write: DIRECT→LOGGED happens when a
  1287	batch opens or a pass starts (edges that precede any write those could
  1288	affect), and LOGGED→DIRECT happens only at the quiescence boundary where the
  1289	overlay's O(1) bulk reset already runs (9.7). In DIRECT mode, writes are
  1290	pure kernel — the benchmark path, the server path, boot before React
  1291	schedules anything, and every idle-time write from timers, sockets, and
  1292	stores while React has nothing in flight. Zero overlay instructions.
  1293	
  1294	In `LOGGED` mode, **every write is logged** — urgent or deferred, watcher or
  1295	no watcher. This mirrors React exactly: a `setState` always enqueues an
  1296	update object; our log record is that update, externalized into an arena
  1297	(and cheaper to allocate). Trying to be cleverer — skipping the log for
  1298	urgent writes when "nothing could tell the difference" — is unsound. The
  1299	proof case: an event handler does an urgent `atom.set(x)` while a
  1300	default-priority batch from earlier in the same event is still pending, and
  1301	then calls `flushSync`. React renders the flushSync work *without* the
  1302	default-priority batch — a legitimate render of a world in which the urgent
  1303	write has happened but the earlier batch has not. If the urgent write had
  1304	skipped the log and gone straight to the canonical value, nothing could
  1305	reconstruct that older world; only a log entry lets the flushSync render
  1306	answer correctly. Note that this write is inside an open batch, so the
  1307	quiescence gate logs it. Two structurally cheaper gates were considered and
  1308	rejected as unsound; their counterexamples are permanent tests (below).
  1309	
  1310	**The loose contract (the default, documented plainly).** A write made while
  1311	React is *fully quiescent* commits immediately: it is applied to canonical
  1312	state with no receipt, and it is visible to every subsequent render pass —
  1313	including a later `flushSync` — because by the time any pass exists, the
  1314	write is simply part of committed history. What such a write does **not** do
  1315	is inherit the lane of the notification it triggers. Concretely, the case
  1316	this gives up: a `setTimeout` fires while React is idle and writes an atom;
  1317	the write commits (DIRECT); the watcher broadcast it triggers schedules
  1318	default-priority React work; then, in the same task, something calls
  1319	`flushSync` — and React renders the flushSync work *without* that
  1320	default-priority batch. React's own `useState` in this schedule would hide
  1321	the timer's value from the flushSync render (its update sits in the excluded
  1322	lane's queue); our signal shows it (it is committed state, and there is no
  1323	receipt from which to reconstruct the pre-write world). This is a deliberate
  1324	deviation from exact React parity, and its shape is bounded: **no write is
  1325	ever lost, and every component converges to the same final state** — the
  1326	worst case is a one-frame window in which a signal-driven component can show
  1327	the newer value while a React-state-driven component shows the older one,
  1328	and that frame can paint. We accept it because the alternative taxes every
  1329	imperative write in every React app forever, for a case that requires an
  1330	idle-time write, a same-task flushSync, and a lane-excluded default batch to
  1331	line up. The exact schedule above is a **contract-documentation test**
  1332	(17.6): it asserts this loose behavior on purpose, so any change to it is a
  1333	deliberate decision, not an accident.
  1334	
  1335	**Exact parity when it matters: `configure({ strictLanes: true })`.** Some
  1336	applications (or test suites) want React-identical lane semantics for
  1337	idle-time writes too. The `strictLanes` option pins the gate to LOGGED
  1338	permanently once the React bindings register — a one-line change to the gate
  1339	predicate, no new machinery, because LOGGED mode's always-log rule already
  1340	provides exact semantics; the quiescence gate exists purely to avoid its
  1341	cost while idle. Under `strictLanes`, the setTimeout/flushSync schedule
  1342	above behaves exactly like `useState`. The same test family runs in both
  1343	configurations, asserting the loose default's documented behavior in one and
  1344	exact parity in the other.
  1345	
  1346	**The two rejected gates, kept as gatekeepers.** (a) *Watcher-count gating*
  1347	("log only once a watcher is mounted") is unsound: the app's first
  1348	`startTransition(() => { atom.set(1); setShow(true) })` writes before any
  1349	watcher exists, goes DIRECT, and leaves no receipt — so the component that
  1350	mounts *during* that transition's render (13.2's marquee case) has no older
  1351	world to read, and urgent renders leak the transition's value. (b)
  1352	*Quiescence-only gating presented as exact parity* fails on the
  1353	setTimeout/flushSync schedule above — the write and the update it schedules
